<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-01T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-01T03:00:00-05:00" n="609" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d609">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.60 f 2/20: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gittings</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Prague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-01T09:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">April 1,
                                        1927—9 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 1—6:57
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>12. Department’s telegram 8, March 22, 4 p.m. Am informed that
                            Czechoslovakia is willing to reopen negotiations. Officials state that
                            upon initiative of Czechoslovak Minister at Washington, they already
                            have prepared a draft which is along the lines of the American-German
                                treaty.<note n="7" xml:id="d609fn7">Treaty of friendship, commerce
                                and consular rights, signed Dec. 8, 1923; <ref target="frus1923v02#pg_29"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                                    29</ref>.</note> Official note promised presently.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gittings</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>